    I've finally had cause to think about WKS seriously and find myself
with a nagging question that I can answer.

    Why are active services indicated using a bit field?  Why not
a sparse array of port values?  I'm asking because I know of projects
around here using port #'s in the 5000 range (I don't know whether
they are approved, or they chose 5000 as something far enough out
of range as not to conflict while they experimented).  That is
a huge number of bytes to build a bit field.   Yet the host which
supports the services at port 5000 is probably only providing about 10
services -- a very small number of bytes in a sparse array of 16
(or 8 or 32) bit ports.

    In general, it seems to me that the total number of bits set
in the bit field is likely to be low compared to the number of bits
necessary to include the bits that are set.

    What am I missing here?

Craig Partridge
